    <item>
      <title>I found Ariella Steinhorn @asteinhorn through her Substack, Nonlinear, where she...</title>
      <link>https://www.instagram.com/p/DOYlXmPjZsu/</link>
      <description><![CDATA[<p><img src="https://scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com/v/t51.82787-15/543692186_18529688707060401_7076398115277526920_n.jpg?stp=dst-jpg_e35_p1080x1080_sh2.08_tt6&amp;_nc_cat=109&amp;ig_cache_key=MzcxNzg4NTgzMTg2MTMyODMxOQ%3D%3D.3-ccb7-5&amp;ccb=7-5&amp;_nc_sid=58cdad&amp;efg=eyJ2ZW5jb2RlX3RhZyI6InhwaWRzLjE0NDB4MTkyMC5zZHIuQzMifQ%3D%3D&amp;_nc_ohc=7rgo1Gb1zVQQ7kNvwGbOwA7&amp;_nc_oc=AdpKJU4vdEN4TLjayeUkF58jtAg_X_IxH4RmqifVXkrl8VKLiFbM3Fc6AdQ1bQ_hoYY&amp;_nc_ad=z-m&amp;_nc_cid=0&amp;_nc_zt=23&amp;_nc_ht=scontent-cph2-1.cdninstagram.com&amp;_nc_gid=tqg8s_qzzkvFEgKEwG7xOw&amp;_nc_ss=7a338&amp;oh=00_AfwbkPAFxUdYwQx3lno97hdnFFXwaxs1WCo9UQFtKeUrgw&amp;oe=69C8E518" alt="Instagram billede fra @asteinhorn" /></p><p><strong>@asteinhorn</strong></p><p>I found Ariella Steinhorn @asteinhorn through her Substack, Nonlinear, where she writes with scroll-stopping vulnerability about power dynamics, work culture, relationships, and love. <br/>
<br/>
So it’s fitting that I fell in love with her writing the way one might fall in love with a person. Her words spoke to me: poignant, poetic and peppered with common ground language tantamount to wordless chemistry between two people. <br/>
<br/>
Beyond our shared interest in those “who don’t fit the usual mold or boxes,” our common ground was comms. <br/>
<br/>
Like me, Ariella was paid to wield her pen, crafting media-friendly narratives and ghostwriting for the employers that hired her.<br/>
<br/>
Unlike me, her brief but life-altering time at behemoths including Uber and a subsidiary of WeWork exposed her to the dark underbelly of tech overlords, who insisted on sanitized versions of truth for the sake of profit over people. <br/>
<br/>
Her words were her livelihood, but also her power. <br/>
<br/>
So when Ariella’s words were taken from her, twisted and defiled by high-ranking men and the systems designed to protect them, she was effectively stripped of that power. <br/>
<br/>
She has since reclaimed it by amplifying voices that have been silenced – from whistleblowers at Palantir to Boeing – which she brilliantly illuminates alongside journalist Eli Rosenberg in her second Substack, Hard Reset. <br/>
<br/>
It is this fearlessness in holding power accountable that struck me about Ariella when I first met her, whose petite frame and pixie-like face seem at odds with her outsized boldness. <br/>
<br/>
But I quickly learned in my conversation with the fellow logophile that the real gift of giving voice to others was that she found her own. <br/>
<br/>
Read on for Ariella’s wisdom on why living truthfully is non-negotiable, and trusting the world will catch you. <br/>
<br/>
#hardreset #nonlinear #substack</p>]]></description>
