<br/>
Unlike me, her brief but life-altering time at behemoths including Uber and a subsidiary of WeWork exposed her to the dark underbelly of tech overlords, who insisted on sanitized versions of truth for the sake of profit over people. <br/>
<br/>
Her words were her livelihood, but also her power. <br/>
<br/>
So when Ariella’s words were taken from her, twisted and defiled by high-ranking men and the systems designed to protect them, she was effectively stripped of that power. <br/>
<br/>
She has since reclaimed it by amplifying voices that have been silenced – from whistleblowers at Palantir to Boeing – which she brilliantly illuminates alongside journalist Eli Rosenberg in her second Substack, Hard Reset. <br/>
<br/>
It is this fearlessness in holding power accountable that struck me about Ariella when I first met her, whose petite frame and pixie-like face seem at odds with her outsized boldness. <br/>
